        <h2>Historical context: Hungary and National Socialist forced labor</h2>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-xl-8 mb-2">
                <p class="abstract">
                    The collapse of Austria-Hungary at the end of the First World War led to a comprehensive reorganization of the 
                    states of southeastern Europe from 1918 onward. In 1920, Hungary had to cede two thirds of its previous territory 
                    to neighboring and successor states such as the newly formed Czechoslovakia or Romania according to the Treaty of 
                    Trianon. The recovery of these territories and the restoration of a “Greater Hungary” was a central political goal 
                    of the Hungarian revanchists, who also promoted Hungary’s alliance with National Socialist Germany for this 
                    purpose.<sup><a href="#endnote1" id="footnote1">1</a></sup><br/>
                    Under pressure from Germany, a southern part of Czechoslovakia was initially occupied and annexed by Hungary in 
                    1938 and, after the final destruction of Czechoslovakia by Germany in 1939, the Transcarpathian region as well. 
                    Romania was also forced by the Axis powers to cede parts of its territory to Hungary in 1940. After the German and 
                    Italian attack on the Kingdom of Yugoslavia, Hungary also annexed areas in the northern part of the 
                    country.<sup><a href="#endnote2" id="footnote2">2</a></sup> The Jewish population of these regions, inhabited by a 
                    large number of different population groups with different languages and religions, thus shared the fate of the 
                    other Hungarian Jews and even today is often seen as part of this group in research and commemorative contexts, even 
                    though members of that population only partly saw themselves as Hungarian or spoke Hungarian. In 1941, Jews from 
                    the annexed territories made up approximately 45 percent of the Jewish population of what was then 
                    Hungary.<sup><a href="#endnote3" id="footnote3">3</a></sup>
                    This website therefore uses the phrasing “deported from Hungary.”
                </p>
