        <h3 class="mt-4">Antisemitism in Hungary</h3>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <p>
                    In 1941, Hungary entered the Second World War as an ally of Nazi Germany. This exacerbated the situation for the 
                    Jewish population.<sup><a href="#endnote4" id="footnote4">4</a></sup> Jews in Hungary had already been subject to 
                    discriminatory legislation since the 1920s, to which further laws were added after the country entered the war. 
                    Male Jews who were excluded from military service were assigned to forced labor battalions at the front, where an 
                    estimated 15,000 of them perished.<sup><a href="#endnote5" id="footnote5">5</a></sup> In 1941, marriages between 
                    Jewish and non-Jewish partners were also banned and the definition of who was to be considered Jewish was broadened. 
                    In future, not only religious affiliation was decisive, but also descent.<sup><a href="#endnote6" id="footnote6">6</a></sup>
                    Then, at the end of August 1941, some 18,000 Jews who had either previously fled to Hungary from other countries to 
                    escape the Nazis or who were unable to prove their Hungarian citizenship quickly enough were deported from 
                    Transcarpathia to German-occupied territories as “alien” Jews. There they were murdered in the Kamenez-Podolsk 
                    massacre along with local Jews by members of the German Order Police and the SS. The extent to which Ukrainian and 
                    Hungarian units were also involved is disputed. A total of 23,600 persons were murdered in the largest mass shooting 
                    and killing operation of the Holocaust up to that time, including about 14,000 to 16,000 Jews deported from 
                    Hungary.<sup><a href="#endnote7" id="footnote7">7</a></sup> A massacre also took place by Hungarian gendarmerie 
                    in the annexed territories of former Yugoslavia, in which approximately 2,550 Serbs and 700 Jews were 
                    murdered.<sup><a href="#endnote8" id="footnote8">8</a></sup> The Hungarian government initially refused to hand 
                    over the Jews, who were considered Hungarian, to the German Reich, meaning that they were spared deportation to 
                    the extermination camps for the time being.<sup><a href="#endnote9" id="footnote9">9</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    As an Axis victory became increasingly unlikely in 1943, the Hungarian government – like Italy before it – began 
                    to establish secret contact with the Allies. After Italy had actually signed an armistice with the Allies in 
                    September 1943 and dissolved the alliance with Nazi Germany, a repetition of these events in Hungary was to be 
                    prevented. In March 1944, Hungary was therefore occupied by German troops and a new government was installed, with 
                    the head of state Miklós Horthy retaining his office.<sup><a href="#endnote10" id="footnote10">10</a></sup>
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-4">
                <div class="infobox mt-2">
                    <h4>&#9432; Jewish men and women</h4>
                    <p>
                        The Jewish men and women deported from Hungary belonged to various communities and religious movements within 
                        Judaism. Not all of them necessarily defined themselves as Jewish. Neither their religion nor their cultural 
                        affiliation to Judaism or self-identification was decisive for their persecution by the National Socialists. 
                        At the heart of the National Socialist worldview was a racist antisemitism that defined Jews according to their 
                        descent. Christians and atheists were also persecuted as Jews by the National Socialists, regardless of their 
                        self-definition or cultural affiliation, if they met their criteria of descent. Not all of the persons referred 
                        to here as Jews identified themselves as Jewish, but they were all persecuted as Jewish.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="mt-4">Deportations of Jews under German occupation</h3>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <p>
                    A special unit of the SS, the “Sondereinsatzkommando Eichmann,” arrived in Hungary along with the German 
                    occupying forces. Under the leadership of Adolf Eichmann, this unit was to organize the deportation of 
                    Hungary’s Jews.<sup><a href="#endnote11" id="footnote11">11</a></sup> Immediately after the German occupation, 
                    the Jewish population was initially obliged to wear a star and then forced into ghettos from April 1944 onward. 
                    The first deportations to the Auschwitz concentration and extermination camp complex began as early as May 1944. 
                    The former Czechoslovakian and Romanian regions of Hungary were among the first areas from which the Jewish 
                    population was deported, as it was feared that they would soon be liberated by the Red Army. As well, the 
                    deportation of the Jews there seemed to the Hungarian government to be less of a domestic political risk. 
                    In less than two months, the National Socialists deported about 437,000 Jews to Auschwitz-Birkenau with assistance 
                    by the Hungarian gendarmerie.<sup><a href="#endnote12" id="footnote12">12</a></sup>
                </p>
                <div>
                    <img class="img-fluid" src="{{ asset('images/history/Auschwitz-Album_268_4.jpg') }}"
                         alt="Arrival of Jewish men, women and children in Auschwitz-Birkenau"/>
