                        Arrival of Jewish men, women and children from Transcarpathia in Auschwitz-Birkenau in May 1944 before the 
                        selection. The photos were taken by SS men for an unknown purpose and represent their perspective. The photos 
                        are one of the few photographic sources from the extermination camps. Auschwitz album
                        (<a href="https://www.yadvashem.org/yv/de/exhibitions/album_auschwitz/arrival.asp" title="Website Yad Vashem">
                            https://www.yadvashem.org/yv/de/exhibitions/album_auschwitz/arrival.asp</a>), Copyright © 2024 Yad Vashem – 
                            The World Holocaust Remembrance Center, use according to Fair Use
                        (<a href="https://www.yadvashem.org/terms-and-conditions.html" title="Website Yad Vashem">
                            https://www.yadvashem.org/terms-and-conditions.html</a>)
                    </p>
                </div>
                <p>
                    The SS murdered the majority of them immediately after their arrival in the gas chambers in Birkenau. 
                    Only about a quarter were picked out during the “selections” to perform forced labor for the German 
                    Reich.<sup><a href="#endnote13" id="footnote13">13</a></sup> Some of the prisoners were deployed in labor 
                    detachments directly in the Auschwitz camp complex, for example in the industrial plants set up there. 
                    During their time in Auschwitz, the prisoners were in constant danger of being singled out for murder in new 
                    “selections.” Another group was selected for work detachments in one of the more than one thousand satellite 
                    camps within the National Socialist concentration camp system that were located at various industrial sites in 
                    the German Reich or in the occupied territories.<sup><a href="#endnote14" id="footnote14">14</a></sup>
                </p>
