        <h3 class="mt-4" id="zwangsarbeit">Forced labor under National Socialism</h3>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <p>
                    National Socialist Germany made extensive use of forced labor in various forms to meet its labor needs. In the 
                    German Reich alone, over 13.5 million persons had to perform forced labor during the Second World 
                    War.<sup><a href="#endnote15" id="footnote15">15</a></sup> For ideological reasons and domestic political 
                    considerations, the National Socialists refused to increase the number of women in gainful employment, so that 
                    foreign workers were used instead.<sup><a href="#endnote16" id="footnote16">16</a></sup>
                    However, as the recruitment of voluntary civilian workers, so-called “alien workers,” in the allied states and 
                    the occupied territories fell far short of the expectations of the National Socialist rulers, from 1940 onward 
                    entire birth cohorts were sometimes conscripted or deported by force. After the invasion of the Soviet Union, people 
                    from the Soviet Union, so-called “Eastern European workers,” quickly formed the largest group of civilian forced 
                    laborers. They were joined by prisoners of war, who were also used for forced labor, as well as concentration camp 
                    inmates.<sup><a href="#endnote17" id="footnote17">17</a></sup> Forced labor was used in all branches of industry, 
                    but also in agriculture and in private households. Forced laborers were thus a visible part of everyday life in 
                    National Socialist Germany, especially in the final years of the war. The camps in which they were quartered were 
                    located in residential areas as well and they shared their workplaces and routes to work with German 
                    civilians.<sup><a href="#endnote18" id="footnote18">18</a></sup> An overview of the known camps and workplaces of 
                    forced laborers in Hamburg can be found <a href="https://zwangsarbeit-in-hamburg.de/"
                       title="Website on forced labor of the Hamburg State Center for Political Education (Landeszentrale für 
                       Politische Bildung Hamburg)">here</a>, for example.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The individual living and working conditions of the forced laborers depended on their legal status, nationality, 
                    gender, and place of work. People from Poland and the Soviet Union in particular were at the mercy of the 
                    arbitrariness and violence of their foremen and guards, and they were often forced to live and work in inhumane 
                    conditions. Even more brutal and inhumane were the working conditions of the Soviet prisoners of war, 1.3 million 
                    of whom did not survive. Together with the concentration camp prisoners, they formed the lowest end of the racist 
                    and social Darwinist hierarchy of National Socialist forced labor. The hard physical labor, deliberately induced 
                    malnutrition, and inadequate provisions made survival impossible for many prisoners. They were murdered by the 
                    National Socialists through the conditions under which they were forced to work and 
                    live.<sup><a href="#endnote19" id="footnote19">19</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Wolfgang Sofsky therefore coined the term “terror work” for the labor of the concentration camp inmates to 
                    emphasize that the purpose of the work was not their productivity, but that the ineffective work assignments 
                    primarily served to terrorize the detainees. The historian Marc Buggeln explicitly rejects this term for the work 
                    in the Neuengamme satellite camps, arguing that the maximum exploitation of the prisoners’ labor until they died 
                    of exhaustion was in the economic interests of the companies. Instead, he advocates the term “slave labor,” which 
                    is also used by many survivors.<sup><a href="#endnote20" id="footnote20">20</a></sup>
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-4">
            </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="mt-4">Forced labor of Jews deported from Hungary</h3>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <p>
                    After other labor reservoirs for forced labor had already been exhausted in 1944, the National Socialists decided to 
                    deport Jews from extermination camps as well to industrial sites in the German Reich in 1944. Some 200,000 Jews were 
                    subsequently deported to concentration camps and their satellite camps in the German Reich, including about 
                    110,000 Jews who had previously been deported from Hungary.<sup><a href="#endnote21" id="footnote21">21</a></sup> 
                    In order to limit contact with the civilian population as well as escape opportunities, these concentration camp 
                    prisoners were held in separate satellite camps, which remained under the control of the SS. The SS also insisted 
                    that Jews from Hungary, who were considered to be particularly dangerous in that organization’s antisemitic 
                    worldview, should not be deployed in groups of fewer than 500.<sup><a href="#endnote22" id="footnote22">22</a></sup> 
                    About 5,800 Jewish women who had been deported from Hungary were thus sent from Auschwitz to satellite camps of the 
                    Neuengamme concentration camp, in some cases via Bergen-Belsen or other concentration camps.<sup><a href="#endnote23" id="footnote23">23</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    After the deposition of Miklós Horthy and the coup d’état of the fascist Arrow Cross Party in Hungary in October 
                    1944, supported by the German occupiers, the deportations were resumed in the areas not yet liberated by the Red 
                    Army. Several tens of thousands of Jews were driven on foot to the Austrian border, where they were handed over 
                    to German authorities. They too were subsequently deployed as forced laborers.<sup><a href="#endnote24" id="footnote24">24</a></sup> 
                    Some of them were also deported to northern Germany, such as approximately 840 prisoners who arrived at Neuengamme 
                    main camp in November 1944. Furthermore, a number of male prisoners were also deported to northern Germany via 
                    Auschwitz for forced labor.<sup><a href="#endnote25" id="footnote25">25</a></sup> In addition, some inmates were 
                    deported via Bergen-Belsen to satellite camps of other main camps or arrived in Bergen-Belsen in the course of the 
                    evacuation of many concentration camps at the end of the war. Since over 15,000 names of concentration camp 
                    prisoners from Hungary are known in Bergen-Belsen, representing only a fraction of the actual number due to the 
                    poor source situation, the total number of prisoners deported from Hungary and imprisoned in northwest German 
                    concentration camps was certainly much higher. The overall number of concentration camp prisoners deported from 
                    Hungary who had to perform forced labor in the German Reich is estimated at 176,000.<sup><a href="#endnote26" id="footnote26">26</a></sup>
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-4">
            </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="mt-4">“Extermination through labor” and survival</h3>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <p>
                    The Jewish concentration camp prisoners were used in particular for the physically demanding underground 
                    relocation of the armaments industry, which the National Socialists had switched to by 1943 in view of Allied 
                    air superiority. However, the forced labor of Hungarian Jews was also used in other branches of the armaments 
                    industry and in clearing rubble.<sup><a href="#endnote27" id="footnote27">27</a></sup>
                </p>
                <img class="img-fluid" src="{{ asset('images/history/Bremen-Innenstadt.jpg') }}"
                     alt="Female concentration camp prisoners from Hungary and Poland clearing rubble in downtown Bremen"/>
                <p class="caption">
                    Female concentration camp prisoners from Hungary and Poland clearing rubble in downtown Bremen. The work of the 
                    concentration camp prisoners was a visible part of everyday life, as the presence of the civilians on the left 
                    of the picture shows. Bremen State Archives, 4.77/1 photos 3567, photo: Walter Cüppers, Bremen, 1944.
                </p>
                <p>
                    In many workplaces, the working conditions were such that survival was not possible in the long term. Thousands 
                    of prisoners were murdered by the National Socialists in the course of “extermination through labor.”<sup><a href="#endnote28" id="footnote28">28</a></sup> 
                    The prisoners’ chances of survival depended not least on the work assignments they were given. In order to prevent 
                    the liberation of the concentration camp prisoners by the Allies, their camps were evacuated before the approaching 
                    front. The prisoners were deported by train or on foot to concentration camps still under German control. 
                    Many prisoners perished on these transports, which survivors characterized as death marches. Only about 63 percent 
                    of the Jews deported to Germany who had previously been deported from Hungary survived the Nazi forced labor.<sup><a href="#endnote29" id="footnote29">29</a></sup>
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-4">
            </div>
        </div>

